  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p>Common questions about travel credit cards</p></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">How do I access airport lounges with my travel credit card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Most travel credit cards provide lounge access through either Priority Pass, Dreamfolks, or the card network's own program (Visa Infinite, Mastercard World). Simply present your credit card and a valid boarding pass at the lounge reception desk. Some banks also issue a separate Priority Pass membership card linked to your credit card account. Each card specifies the number of complimentary visits per year (typically 4-12) — visits beyond the limit are charged at $27-$35 per visit.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can I transfer reward points to airline frequent flyer programs?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, premium travel cards like HDFC Infinia and Diners Club Black allow 1:1 transfers to airline programs such as Singapore Airlines KrisFlyer, InterMiles (Jet Airways successor), and Marriott Bonvoy. Axis Atlas allows transfers to Air India and Vistara programs. The transfer ratio varies — HDFC Infinia offers the best value at 1 reward point = 1 airmile. Transfer typically processes within 2-7 business days. This is the most valuable way to redeem travel card rewards, especially for premium class redemptions.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What travel insurance comes with travel credit cards?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Travel credit cards typically include: (1) Air accident insurance covering ₹50 lakh to ₹1 crore, (2) Lost baggage reimbursement of $500-$1,000, (3) Trip cancellation/interruption cover, (4) Emergency medical expenses abroad, (5) Purchase protection against theft or damage for items bought with the card. Coverage is automatic — no separate activation needed — as long as the travel was booked using the card. Always check your specific card's insurance terms for coverage limits, exclusions, and claim procedures.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What is the difference between air miles and reward points?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Air miles (like InterMiles or KrisFlyer miles) can only be redeemed for flights, upgrades, and travel-related redemptions within a specific airline's loyalty program. Reward points (like HDFC Reward Points or Axis EDGE Points) are more flexible and can be redeemed for flights, hotels, merchandise, vouchers, or statement credits. Some premium cards allow converting reward points into air miles, giving you the best of both worlds. Air miles typically offer higher value per point on premium flight redemptions compared to general reward points.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is a travel credit card worth it if I travel only 2-3 times a year?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, a mid-tier travel card can still be worthwhile. Even with 2-3 trips per year, you'll benefit from: 4-6 lounge visits (worth ₹8,000-₹12,000), travel insurance coverage, and accumulated air miles from everyday spending that can fund a free flight. Cards like SBI Elite (₹4,999/year) or Amex Platinum Travel (₹5,000/year) deliver benefits worth ₹15,000-₹25,000 for moderate travellers. However, if you rarely travel, a general rewards or cashback card would provide more practical value for your spending pattern.</div></div></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

